postcontent: I really hate to sell this, but I need to cash for an unexpected bill.After building many ARs over the years, I wanted to try one in 7.62x39. I've always loved the caliber (ever since my SKS), since it hits nearly as hard as a 308 at medium range, and is WAY cheaper to shoot.Anyway, it came out better than I ever expected, I just don't have much time to shoot anymore, and as noted above, the money is needed alsewhere...Details of the build: - Anderson Mfg upper and lower - Faxon Firearms 16" Barrel** This barrel is the focal point of the build, since I was hoping to one day get a suppressor and shoot subs    Here's the details direct from Faxon:    Give your AR-15 some Russian love! 4150 QPQ coated inside and out for amazing corrosion resistance and durability.     We chose to offer the 1/8 twist so reloaders and those shooting heavier grain 147s can use their weapon effectively. Provides great accuracy for all loads!    Faxon Firearms barrels are the pinnacle of value. Manufactured 100% in-house from cradle-to-grave, these barrels are button-rifled and air-guage tested to ensure superior accuracy.    All barrels are manufactured under our ISO:9001 and AS:9100 (pending) quality certifications. We inspect each barrel over 15 times before it ever reaches you.     Barrel Material: 4150 CMV Steel     Barrel Type: Button Rifled     Barrel Caliber: 7.62x39mm Russian    Barrel Twist: 1:8    Barrel Length: 16"    Barrel Profile: Gov't/SOCOM    Barrel Gas System: Mid Length    Inside Finish: QPQ Nitride    Outside Finish: QPQ Nitride    Muzzle Thread: 5/8 x24 TPI (Threads Per Inch)    Gas Block Diameter: .750"    Gas Hole Diameter: .091"    Gas Block Journal Length: 1.9"    Barrel Extension: M4    Weight: 1.67 lbs    Magnetic Particle Inspected!    11-degree Target Crown- Nickel Boron Nitride M16 (fully shrouded) carrier group and bolt, all properly staked and high grade. Very slick (pun intended) and easy to clean- low profile gas block- Ultra slim 15" free floating Keymod handguard with cover inserts and custom 3D printed "7.62x39" TPM vibration-absorbing endcap. Can be removed if you prefer to have an open ended handguard.- 6-position butt stock with 4 QD sling cups and 1 QD sling swivel- Ambidextrous tactical charging handle- Polymer BUIS (back-up sights), tan currently installed, but I have a set of black that I'll swap out if you prefer- Tru-Glo multi-reticle reflex sight. It's a cheap optic, but man is it bright and works great. I actually really like it and will be buying another one to replace it if I ever get another AR. It's Red/Green switchable and is clearly visible in daylight. It has several reticles, but my favorite is the circle-dot for quick close-up work. If you're hunting with this gun, of course you'll want a proper scope.- 2 ASC stainless 10-round dedicated 7.62x39 magazines. Many people have heard horror stories about getting a 7.62x39 AR to run properly. It seems to come down to 2 things: Feed ramps and magazines. These mags are purpose-built for this round, and seem to be about the best available from my research.- Speaking of feed ramps, I opened up and polished the standard M4-type ramps to eliminate the choke points caused by the larger projectile and shorter geometry of the x39 round vs the 5.56, and it feeds like butter. I've only put about 30 rounds through it, since I was working on subsonic load development, but once I corrected the ramps, I had zero issues from then on.- Custom machined blast-redirecting muzzle device. I machined and Duracoated this one myself. If you're familiar with the Noveske KX3 or the "Flash Can" style of muzzle device, then you get the idea. It directs all the flash and concussion downrange, away from the shooter. It really makes a big difference vs no brake, but of course you can swap it out for any 5/8-24 muzzle device of your choice. You'll see in teh photos what looks like a short silencer. It's a fake can. It's included as well, just for giggles. It's totally useless, and actually probably makes the gun louder, but it looks pretty sweet screwed on, especially with the long hanguard.- Everything packs up and fits (barely) into this sweet little rectangular case that doesn't scream "gun!", which is exactly what I was hoping for. It all breaks down and is well secured for travel as well. There's and outer pouch for mags and small parts that's not visible in the photos. It's a nice padded ballistic nylon case. I'm very pleased with it.Well, that's about it. Feel free to ask any questions. I'm not really looking for trades this time, since I don't want to sell it anyway, but I have to since I just found out I have to spend over a grand on my wife's car. Otherwise, you would NOT be reading this ad right now, and this rifle would stay in my closet where it belongs. The price is also fairly firm, for the above-mentioned reasons.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Browning BDM 9mm
location: Raleigh, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: I have for sale or trade a Browning BDM in 9mm.  The pistol comes with the original box, 10 round factory magazine and what I believe is a MecGar 15 round magazine.  Some wear but overall in good condition.  The pistol is a magazine fed, self-loading, hammer firing type which was designed with a trigger "mode" switch installed on the left-hand side of the slide (actually only a flush inlaid disk with a bisecting groove), toggling between double-action/single-action(DA/SA) pistol mode, and the double-action-only (DAO) or "revolver" mode—though, of course, other than the similarity of the trigger mode, the BDM has no resemblance to revolvers. This mode switch is what gives the handgun its name, with BDM standing for "Browning Dual Mode" or "Browning Double Mode".  For more information check out this excellent article on the BDM: http://www.chuckhawks.com/browning_BPM-D.htmAsking $450.00 but will consider your reasonable offer.  FTF only.  No shipping.  Must have concealed carry or valid purchase permit.  I will prepare a bill of sale for both of us.  Thanks for looking.

You can choose to cheat the system and NOT pay the Oklahoma Tax commission, but you are legally obligated to report it on your Form 511 under the heading of "use tax". And since I have had a few inquiries, (and one REALLY whiney fellow who keeps talking about liberal media) about the price, I'll knock off the tiny bit of markup I had on the gun.
